			<ns0:name>mcgra...@chromium.org</ns0:name><ns0:uri>/u/109286297231979736865/</ns0:uri></ns0:author><ns0:content type="html">Actually EABI says that several options are acceptable, including SIGFPE.
To help developers we should aim for consistency whenever it does not sacrifice other important goals like performance.  For ARMv7, division will be in software and so there is no extra cost to simulating a trap for division by zero.

When we support another processor where division by zero does not normally trap, we can revisit the question for that processor.</ns0:content><ns0:updated>2012-06-13T18:53:24.000Z</ns0:updated><ns0:published>2012-06-13T18:53:24.000Z</ns0:published><ns2:updates /><ns0:title>Comment 2 by mcgra...@chromium.org</ns0:title><ns0:link href="http://code.google.com/p/nativeclient/issues/detail?id=2833#c2" rel="alternate" type="text/html" /><ns0:link href="https://code.google.com/feeds/issues/p/nativeclient/issues/2833/comments/full/2" rel="self" type="application/atom+xml" /></ns0:entry>